Here’s a quick first‑pass survey of the ones you listed, focusing on what makes each interesting and where they sit on the “serious self‑hosted tool” vs “toy/archived” spectrum.

High‑leverage Rust pastebins
rustypaste
rustypaste is a single‑binary file upload + pastebin + URL shortener that stores everything on the filesystem (no DB), with decent auth and lifecycle features.
​

Features: file upload, URL shortening, upload‑from‑URL, one‑shot links, expirations with configurable units, optional dedup, list/delete endpoints, MIME guessing, optional landing page, basic auth with multiple tokens, delete tokens.
​

Ops: binary releases and distro packages, Docker image + compose, trivial config via config.toml, hot‑reloading of config.
​

Fit: Very “curlable”, good for CLI‑driven workflows and scripts, and easy to slap behind Nginx; no DB makes it attractive for minimal deployments.
​

wastebin
wastebin is an axum + sqlite pastebin, single binary, with crypto and a surprisingly polished UX (themes, QR codes, keyboard shortcuts).
​

Features: zstd compression, syntect highlighting, multiple color themes, ChaCha20‑Poly1305 + Argon2 password‑protected pastes, burn‑after‑reading, expirations, QR code for URLs, keyboard navigation, wastebin-ctl for DB maintenance.
​

Ops: sqlite backend, Docker image, docker‑compose, Nix flake (nix run 'github:matze/wastebin#wastebin'), configurable via WASTEBIN_* env vars.
​

Caveats: Explicitly no auth or admin; author warns against exposing it directly to the internet without external rate‑limiting / protection.
​

microbin
microbin is a tiny, self‑contained binary pastebin with both server‑side and client‑side encryption and optional file uploads.
​

Features: single‑file binary, configurable, server‑ and client‑side encryption, file uploads, raw text endpoints; designed to be very low memory/disk footprint.
​

Ops: docker.sh installer that pulls from Docker Hub, cargo install microbin + .env; public demo instance and a dedicated website with docs.
​

Fit: Good if you want “small but not toy,” with encryption built‑in and minimal hosting surface area.
​

bin
bin is a “highly opinionated, minimal pastebin” using Rocket, accepting text and arbitrary binary files (images, PDFs), and shipping a tiny curl‑based client.
​

Features: binary upload support, simple URL scheme, no external SQL server, Rocket config via BIN_* env vars (port, limits, workers, etc.).
​

Ops: Docker image and docker-compose example; uploads stored on a mounted volume.
​

Fit: Very lightweight file dropbox/paste for personal use; lower feature surface than rustypaste/wastebin, but simple.
​

Non‑Rust or marginal for your survey
paste
paste markets itself as a “sensible, modern pastebin” with multiple files, syntax highlighting, anonymity, and secure auth, but tech stack isn’t visible in the snippet and repo content would need a closer read; it’s not clearly Rust‑centric from the brief.
