If you tell me your priorities (e.g. “must be DB‑less”, “must have encryption”, “wants easy Nix integration”, “needs multi‑user auth”), I can narrow this to 1–2 concrete recommendations and point at the exact extension points you’d probably want to tweak.

which one to use as template for best practices and modulariry
For “best practices and modularity,” wastebin is the best template, with rustypaste as a strong second reference.

Why wastebin stands out
Modern stack & clear boundaries. It’s built on axum + sqlite, and the README/API design shows clean separation between HTTP layer, persistence, and configuration (env‑driven config, explicit non‑features like “no auth/admin,” focused core domain).
​

Good operational modeling. It documents binaries, Docker, docker‑compose, Nix flake, and cross‑compiled images, all against the same core binary, which is a good pattern for keeping deployment concerns out of the core app.
​

Well‑defined public API. JSON POST schema, /raw/:id, password header, cookie‑based deletion, plus a separate wastebin-ctl DB admin tool—this separation between user‑facing API and admin tooling is a nice architectural precedent.
​

⠋If you want to emulate a “modular,  reasonably secure public service” with a browser UI, HTTP API, and CLI/Neovim integration, wastebin is the best starting point.
Thinking...​

Why also study rustypaste
Single‑binary, DB‑less design. rustypaste uses the filesystem as its storage layer and keeps configuration in config.toml plus env overrides, which is a clean, modular pattern for a small service.
​

Feature flagging and deployment variants. It has crate feature flags (shuttle, TLS backend choice), packaged binaries, Docker, and Nginx examples, showing a good separation between core crate and deployment integrations.
​

Auth and lifecycle modeling. Basic auth via tokens, separate delete tokens, list endpoint gated by auth, one‑shot links, expirations, and cleanup scripts give concrete patterns for modularizing “policies” around object lifecycles.
​

If your own service is more CLI/file‑centric with minimal UI, rustypaste gives slightly better guidance on file naming, auth token management, and sharable config semantics.
​

How I’d use them as templates
Use wastebin as your reference for: module layout around axum + DB, env‑based configuration, HTTP API surface, and separate admin tooling (wastebin-ctl).
​

Use rustypaste as your reference for: filesystem‑based storage abstraction, config via TOML + env, feature flags, and CLI ergonomics / third‑party client integration.
​

If you describe the architecture you’re aiming for (DB vs flat files, need for encryption, multi‑user, etc.), I can sketch a concrete module breakdown that borrows the specific good parts from both.

